 means by which they were recruited, and includes a number of individuals' stories. It shows how manpower was a major concern for the Admiralty; how the Admiralty put in place a range of recruitment methods including the "a system; how it worried about depleting merchant shipping of sufficient sailors; and how, although most seamen were volunteers, the press gang was resorted to, especially during the initial mobilisation at the beginning of wars and to find certain kinds of particularly skilled seamen. The book also makes comparisons with recruitment methods employed by the navies of other countries and by the British army. J. Ross Dancy is Assistant Professor of History at Sam Houston State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aImpressmentzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aSailorszGreat BritainxHistory. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aMaritime History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Navy.  aFrench Revolutionary Wars.  aImpressment.  aJ. Ross Dancy.  aNapoleonic Wars.  aNaval Manpower.  aPress Gang.  aRecruitment Methods.  aSam Houston State University.  aVolunteers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204471040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782044710423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782044710/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles